headline: US judge will not delay Google search trial for DOJ switch to Trump administration
summary: (Reuters) -A trial on the U.S. Department of Justice's proposals to diminish Google's dominance in online search will not be delayed to give Trump administration officials more time to revise the request, the judge overseeing the case said on Tuesday.  The DOJ has proposed forcing Alphabet's Google to sell its Chrome browser, and potentially the Android mobile operating system, to take away distribution points for Google search.  President-elect Donald Trump expressed skepticism about a Google breakup in October.

headline: Economy at risk without tech innovation: Investor
summary: President-elect Donald Trump’s incoming administration is making waves across various industries, particularly when it comes to regulating Big Tech. Tusk Venture Partners Founder and CEO Bradley Tusk joins Catalysts Co-hosts Seana Smith and Madison Mills to discuss the need for policies that support innovation without hindering growth.  Tusk sees risk to the US economy if early-stage investors, like himself, are unable to support smaller tech companies that could one day challenge today’s industry giants. “If you don't have people, companies kind of waiting in the wings to fill the void when the big players today ultimately grow stagnant, then all of a sudden that's a huge hole in the marketplace that makes us a lot more vulnerable to companies from other countries,” Tusk explains. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Catalysts here. This post was written by Cindy Mizaku.

headline: Google proposes fresh tweaks to search results in Europe
summary: Google has proposed more changes to its search results in Europe after some smaller rivals complained about lower traffic to their sites resulting from previous tweaks by the Alphabet unit and as EU antitrust regulators consider levying charges against the company under new EU tech rules.  Under the Digital Markets Act, Google is prohibited from favouring its products and services on its platform.  The latter three groups said their direct booking clicks have fallen by 30% due to recent Google changes.

headline: Google, Meta urge Australia to delay bill on social media ban for children
summary: Google and Facebook-owner Meta Platforms urged the Australian government on Tuesday to delay a bill that will ban most forms of social media for children under 16, saying more time was needed to assess its potential impact.  Prime Minister Anthony Albanese's centre-left government wants to pass the bill, which represents some of the toughest controls on children's social media use imposed by any country, into law by the end of the parliamentary year on Thursday.
